diagnoses.name: Chronic Myelogenous Leukemia (CML)
diagnoses.description: A type of cancer that starts in the blood-forming cells of the bone marrow and invades the blood. It can cause leukocytosis, thrombocytosis, and, less commonly, rash and edema.

diagnoses.name: Acute Lymphoblastic Leukemia (ALL)
diagnoses.description: A type of cancer of the blood and bone marrow that affects white blood cells. Symptoms can include leukocytosis, lymphadenopathy, and thrombocytosis.

diagnoses.name: Lymphoma (Hodgkin and Non-Hodgkin)
diagnoses.description: A group of blood cancers that develop in the lymphatic system. Symptoms can include lymphadenopathy, thrombocytosis, and leukocytosis.

diagnoses.name: Infectious Mononucleosis
diagnoses.description: Often called mono or the 'kissing disease,' this infectious illness is typically caused by the Epstein-Barr virus and can result in fever, swollen lymph nodes (including cervical lymphadenopathy), and a rash.

diagnoses.name: Rheumatoid Arthritis
diagnoses.description: A chronic inflammatory disorder affecting many joints, including those in the hands and feet. It can cause a maculopapular rash and, in severe cases, lymphadenopathy.

diagnoses.name: Sarcoidosis
diagnoses.description: A disease involving abnormal collections of inflammatory cells that can form as nodules in multiple organs. It can lead to lymphadenopathy, rash, and, in rare cases, thrombocytosis.

diagnoses.name: Kawasaki Disease
diagnoses.description: A condition that causes inflammation in the walls of some blood vessels in the body. It's more common in children. Symptoms include rash, lymphadenopathy, and edema.

diagnoses.name: Rocky Mountain Spotted Fever
diagnoses.description: A bacterial infection transmitted by a tick. Symptoms include a rash, fever, and potential thrombocytosis.

diagnoses.name: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE)
diagnoses.description: A chronic autoimmune disease that can affect any part of the body, manifesting in skin rashes, arthritis, and kidney dysfunction. Symptomatic presentation can include maculopapular rash and lymphadenopathy.

diagnoses.name: Secondary Syphilis
diagnoses.description: The second stage of syphilis, a sexually transmitted infection, marked by skin rash and lymphadenopathy.

diagnoses.description: Migraines are a type of headache characterized by severe pain, often accompanied by nausea, and sensitivity to light and sound (phonophobia). In some cases, they can also cause symptoms like weakness, numbness, and speech disturbances (aphasia).

A stroke occurs when the blood supply to part of the brain is interrupted or reduced, preventing brain tissue from getting oxygen and nutrients. Strokes can cause symptoms such as aphasia, numbness on one side of the body, and weakness.
Sometimes referred to as a 'mini-stroke,' a TIA produces similar symptoms to a stroke, like aphasia, weakness, and numbness, but usually lasts only a few minutes and causes no permanent damage.

MS is a disease of the central nervous system that can lead to symptoms such as numbness, weakness, and, in some cases, difficulties with speech. Some people with MS may also experience sensitivity to sound.

Depending on its location in the brain, a tumor can cause a wide range of neurological symptoms, including aphasia, numbness, and weakness. Sensitivity to sound is less common but can occur depending on specific areas of the brain affected.
An inflammation of the brain and spinal cord membranes, typically caused by an infection. Symptoms can include severe headache, phonophobia, numbness, and weakness among others.

An inflammation of the brain, often caused by a viral infection. Symptoms can mirror those of meningitis and include severe headache, phonophobia, as well as neurological deficits such as weakness, numbness, and in severe cases, aphasia.

A neurological disorder marked by sudden recurrent episodes of sensory disturbance, loss of consciousness, or convulsions, associated with abnormal electrical activity in the brain. It can sometimes cause post-seizure symptoms including aphasia, numbness, and weakness.
An autoimmune disorder where the body's immune system attacks the nerves. Early symptoms include weakness and tingling in the extremities. It can progress to severe weakness and numbness.

Also known as Lou Gehrig's disease, ALS is a type of motor neuron disease that causes the death of neurons controlling voluntary muscles. It primarily causes weakness and muscle wasting, but numbness is not typically a symptom due to its focus on motor rather than sensory neurons.

diagnoses.name: Multiple Sclerosis
diagnoses.description: A chronic, typically progressive disease involving damage to the sheaths of nerve cells in the brain and spinal cord, symptoms may include numbness, impairment of speech and of muscular coordination, blurred vision and severe fatigue.

diagnoses.name: Stroke
diagnoses.description: A condition in which poor blood flow to the brain results in cell death. Symptoms may include inability to move or feel on one side of the body, problems understanding or speaking, dizziness, or loss of vision to one side.

diagnoses.name: Migraine with Aura
diagnoses.description: A type of headache characterized by severe head pain, visual disturbances (aura), nausea, and sensitivity to light. Scintillation or flashing lights can be an aura before the migraine attack.

diagnoses.name: Transient Ischemic Attack
diagnoses.description: Often called a 'mini-stroke', a transient ischemic attack is a brief period of symptoms similar to those in a stroke. It can cause temporary weakness, numbness, and paralysis.

diagnoses.name: Guillain-Barré Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A rare disorder in which your body's immune system attacks your nerves. Weakness and tingling in your extremities are usually the first symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Peripheral Neuropathy
diagnoses.description: A result of damage to your peripheral nerves, often causes weakness, numbness, and pain, usually in your hands and feet. It can also affect other areas and body functions including digestion, urination, and circulation.

diagnoses.name: Diabetic Neuropathy
diagnoses.description: A type of nerve damage that can occur with diabetes. It affects the feet and legs first, followed by the hands and arms. Symptoms include weakness, numbness, tingling, and pain.

diagnoses.name: Vitamin B12 Deficiency
diagnoses.description: This deficiency can cause severe and irreversible damage, especially to the brain and nervous system. Early symptoms may include weakness, tiredness, and light-headedness. Advanced symptoms may include numbness and tingling in the hands and feet.

diagnoses.name: Lyme Disease
diagnoses.description: An infectious disease caused by the Borrelia bacterium which is spread by ticks. Early symptoms may include fever, headache, and fatigue, but it can also lead to neurological problems like paresthesia and weakness if not treated.

diagnoses.name: Amyotrophic Lateral Sclerosis (ALS)
diagnoses.description: A nervous system disease that weakens muscles and impacts physical function. Symptoms include muscle weakness, tightness (spasticity), and gradually worsening paralysis.

diagnoses: Metabolic disorders such as hypothyroidism or vitamin B12 deficiency

diagnoses.name: Multiple Sclerosis
diagnoses.description: A chronic illness involving your central nervous system. The immune system attacks myelin, which is the protective layer around your nerve fibers, leading to delayed response times and symptoms like numbness and problems with coordination.

diagnoses.name: Stroke
diagnoses.description: Occurs when the blood supply to part of your brain is interrupted or reduced, preventing brain tissue from getting oxygen and nutrients. Brain cells start to die in minutes. Symptoms can include sudden numbness, confusion, trouble speaking, and loss of balance or coordination.

diagnoses.name: Migraine
diagnoses.description: A neurological condition that can cause multiple symptoms. It's frequently characterized by intense, debilitating headaches. Symptoms may include nausea, difficulty speaking, numbness or tingling, and sensitivity to light and sound.

diagnoses.name: Transient Ischemic Attack (TIA)
diagnoses.description: Often called a mini-stroke, a transient ischemic attack is a brief, temporary disruption of blood supply to your brain. It can produce similar symptoms to a stroke but usually lasts only a few minutes and causes no permanent damage.

diagnoses.name: Brain Tumor
diagnoses.description: A brain tumor is a mass or growth of abnormal cells in your brain. Many different types of brain tumors exist. Some brain tumors are noncancerous (benign), and some brain tumors are cancerous (malignant). Symptoms can include headaches, numbness, balance issues, and difficulty with speech.

diagnoses.name: Diabetic Neuropathy
diagnoses.description: A type of nerve damage that can occur with diabetes. High blood sugar (glucose) can injure nerves throughout your body. Diabetic neuropathy most often damages nerves in your legs and feet, causing numbness, pain, and sensitivity.

diagnoses.name: Meningitis
diagnoses.description: An inflammation of the fluid and membranes (meninges) surrounding your brain and spinal cord. The swelling from meningitis typically triggers symptoms like headache, fever, and a stiff neck. It can also lead to a decreased consciousness and neurological deficits.

diagnoses.name: Lyme Disease
diagnoses.description: An infectious disease caused by the Borrelia bacterium which is spread by ticks. It can cause neurological problems, including meningitis, facial palsy, and neuropathy, causing numbness and weakness in the limbs.

diagnoses.name: Neurosyphilis
diagnoses.description: A bacterial infection of the brain or spinal cord. It usually occurs in people who have had untreated syphilis for many years. Neurosyphilis can cause headache, difficulty coordinating muscle movements, paralysis, sensory deficits, and dementia.

diagnoses.name: Guillain-Barre Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A rare disorder in which your body's immune system attacks your nerves. Weakness and tingling in your extremities are usually the first symptoms. These sensations can quickly spread, eventually paralyzing your whole body.
